latestPosts.caption:
At the end of December last year I experienced my first diving experience in Phi Phi, Thailand. I was there for a shoot in Bangkok and then decided to extend my trip and explore the islands of Thailand, when scuba happened. Did 2 long dives in a day and instantly fell in love with the underwater so much so that in between those 2 dives, I had already decided that I’m gonna be perusing this. Not even a year has completed since then and I kept my promise to myself. I’m a certified open water diver now under @paditv 

My instructor @panda_biker is the best instructor I could have asked for. He made this so smooth for me.
Thank you Panda 🫰🏽

I’m so glad to be doing this course in my home country as it gives a lot of comfort level and better understanding within the community. I chose @thedivemasterhavelock and honestly, I am so glad I did. They are family now. They made so comfortable during the whole process, and gave me the best experience I could have asked for and even more.

This pictures are taken by @abhishek.krishnan.77 I mean woooowwwww bro🥲

#padi #paditv #divetogether #scubadiver #diving #openwaterdivingcourse #havelockisland

These are the editing apps I use 📱👇🏽

For Video Editing: VN & Edits by Instagram

For Colour Grading and Filters: VSCO and Tone 

For Texts and Effects: Tone and Prequel 

For Creativity: Canva

•I have subscription to all of these apps for unlimited tools and options.

•The composition while taking the videos and photos is more important than editing 

•I don’t like over editing and just bringing it closer to natural

•I love to use grains for film camera effect and play with Highlights and Shadows

These are my settings 📱👇🏽

1. I set my camera video settings (I have a IPhone 15 ) to 4k and 60FPS - this way you’ll maintain high-quality even when you want to use slow-motion effects

2. Turn off HDR in your camera settings - super important as Instagram just doesn’t accept HDR videos - > text overlays and colors will seem faded after posting

3. If you use a third-party app for editing (like VN, InShot) make sure to export your video in the highest quality again and again that Smart HDR is turned off.

4. Go to your Instagram settings, select “Media Quality” and turn on “Upload Highest Quality” - in your standard settings this is turned off to save data so definitely go and double-check this

5. Kinda obvious but still: clean your lens EVERY SINGLE TIME before recording anything. 

6.Also, I have bought 2TB iCloud storage, as shooting in such High Resolution requires a lot of space and content creation is my job, so I don’t mind this monthly investment. 

If you have any other tips, share them in the comments!!
